07053nam a22009975i 9789048544257DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485442577 a10.1515/97890485442572doi  a(DE-B1597)572716  a(OCoLC)1200846337  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aFAM0000002bisacsh00aKeeping Family in an Age of Long Distance Trade, Imperial Expansion, and Exile, 1550-1850 /ced. by Heather Dalton. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Images, Maps, and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Keeping Family -- tPart 1. Surviving Slavery, Transportation and Forced Labour -- t1 Shaping Family Identity among Korean Migrant Potters in Japan during the Tokugawa Period -- t2 Forced Separations -- t3 ‘If I Should Fall Behind’ -- tPart 2. On the Road: Mobility, Wellbeing, and Survival -- t4 The Witch Who Moved to the Wilderness -- t5 Independence, Affection and Mobility in Eighteenth-Century Scotland -- tPart 3. In the Absence of Family, Support in Unfamiliar Environments -- t6 Relationships Lost and Found in the Mid-Sixteenth-Century Iberian Atlantic -- t7 ‘Grieved in My Soul that I Suffered You to Depart from Me’ -- tPart. 4 Managing Kinship-Based Businesses and Trading Networks -- t8 New Christian Family Networks in the First Visitation of the Inquisition to Brazil -- t9 Intimate Affairs -- tPart 5. Ensuring the Survival of Maritime Families -- t10 ‘These Happy Effects on the Character of the British Sailor’ -- t11 Maintaining the Family -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Persons0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKeeping Family in an Age of Long Distance Trade, Imperial Expansion and Exile, 1550-1850 brings together eleven original essays by an international group of scholars, each investigating how family, or the idea of family, was maintained or reinvented when husbands, wives, children, apprentices, servants or slaves separated, or faced separation, from their household. The result is a fresh and geographically wide-ranging discussion about the nature of family and its intersection with travel over a three hundred year period during which roles and relationships, within and between households, were increasingly affected by trade, settlement, and empire building. The imperial project may have influenced different regions in different ways at different times yet, as this collection reveals, families, especially those transcending national ties and traditional boundaries were central to its progress. Together, these essays bring new understandings of the foundations of our interconnected world and of the people who contributed to it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aFamiliesxHistory. 0aLong-distance relationshipsxHistory. 0aSeparation (Psychology). 0aSocial interactionxHistory. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aModern History. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh  aFAMILY and EMOTION MIGRATION and SETTLEMENT TRANSPORTATION and SLAVERY MERCHANTS and TRADE RACE and GENDER.1 aBarclay, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBregoli, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroomhall, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutter, Nat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalton, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalton, Heather, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/e